f <em>Echinicola</em> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><em>Echinicola</em> (E.chi.ni.co′la. L. masc. n. <em>echinus</em> -<em>i</em> sea urchin; L. suff. -<em>cola</em> derived from L. masc. or fem. n. <em>incola</em> a dweller; N.L. fem. n. <em>Echinicola</em> a sea-urchin dweller).</s></p><p class="description"><s>Rod-shaped cells, motile by gliding.</s><s>Gram-negative.</s><s>Do not form endospores.</s><s>Can ferment d-glucose.</s><s>Produce non-diffusible carotenoid pigments.</s><s>Chemo-organotrophs.</s><s>Positive for cytochrome oxidase, catalase and alkaline phosphatase.</s><s>The major respiratory quinone is MK-7.</s><s>The main cellular fatty acids are straight-chain unsaturated and branched-chain unsaturated fatty acids C<sub>15 : 0</sub> iso, C<sub>16 : 1</sub><em>ω</em>5<em>c</em>, C<sub>17 : 1</sub> iso <em>ω</em>9<em>c</em>, C<sub>17 : 1</sub><em>ω</em>6<em>c</em>, C<sub>15 : 0</sub> iso 3-OH, C<sub>17 : 0</sub> iso 3-OH and summed feature 3, comprising C<sub>15 : 0</sub> iso 2-OH and/or C<sub>16 : 1</sub><em>ω</em>7<em>c</em>.</s><s>As determined by 16S rRNA gene sequence analysis, the genus <em>Echinicola</em> is a member of the phylum <em>Bacteroidetes</em>.</s><s>The type species is <em>Echinicola pacifica</em>.</s></p></content></protolog>